			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Soloing tactics that still work?<a name="65546"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 4 04 11:14 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>First, I don't believe you have started too late.  Despite the whining about the AOE nerf... Bards are still one of the most interesting and fun classes in the game in my opinion.  And still remarkably solo-capable up to at least 65.  In the 60's though, there are grouping possibilities that will overshadow soloing, soloing is best for while you are lfg.
<br />

<br />
At 30 there are a number of options open too you.  Its a period where there is a lot to learn about being a bard.  I disagree with Moose on melee soloing into the 50s being the way to go.  Be sure to group as well as solo to learn all your capabilities,
<br />

<br />
Fear Kiting.
<br />
This has been possible for a few levels.  Find a pull-to spot where mobs will run in a safe direction for a while... pull... snare... screech(fear)...haste... beat down.  Pick a spot to be the end of your run... if you get there, let fear break and run back to the starting point and refear.
<br />

<br />
This can also work in duos/trios/groups-light-on-healing.  Duoing with a rogue when fear kiting is NICE
<br />

<br />
Chant kiting,
<br />
Mind-numbingly slow at 30 because you only have fufils chant.  You just run and dot the mob, never being in a bit of danger because you arent close to the mob.  You can add 1 or 2 ticks of bellow to add to the damage until you get more chants (1 chant every 4 levels).  You will use this to take the last bit off in charms and swarms.
<br />

<br />
Charm Kiting.
<br />
This has changed from when I did it as I understand things.  Your pet will not likely be the winner in a 1-on-1 charm kite anymore.  He will be doing half damage.  Thats still oK you can plan to kill the pet and charm the opponent afterwards.  What I would do is start by landing a chant on me would-be-pet.. then charming him, and sending him into the fight.  I suggest the following 2-line hotkey
<br />

<br />
/pet attack
<br />
/pet target
<br />

<br />
That way you immediately retarget him .. when he breaks.. run... chant... charm... swap targets...  hit key
<br />

<br />
Your pet will surely die first in that he is taking your chant damage and the other mobs damage... when he gets low either break charm with invis or decide not to recharm and kite him down with chant kiting.
<br />

<br />
Swarm Kiting (Charm kiting kicked up a notch)
<br />
Once mastered, hands down the best soloing tactic available to the bard today.  It is because of swarm kiting that I cautioned earlier to spend some time grouping too.
<br />

<br />
You need &quot;social mobs&quot;, mobs that will assist one another when they are attacked.  Cougars in iceclad... spectres in oasis... aviaks in timorous deep...giants and wolves in GD... there are tons of them out there.
<br />
You need a pull to spot that is off the beaten path.  You will have soft aggro and its easy to train folks  so stay away from em.
<br />

<br />
This is much the same as charm kiting now.  You expect your pet to be the one to die.. but a LOT faster.  You are going to break the charm with invis most likely, rather than wait for a break.  You are gonna want that same attack/target hotkey.  You will NOT be chanting your pet to start.  
<br />

<br />
Gather a group of social mobs.. I would start small till you get the hang of it and work your way up.  Lets say you got 4 mobs for your first one... Charm one... target a second.. pet attack/pet target... all 3 of the mobs beat on your pet.  you recharm him til he is approaching 10% health... then invis to break charm before 0%.  Your chant down the skinny remains of your ex pet.. then charm what he was attacking and do it again.. and again.. this would be a straight charm kite if you did'nt grab any adds and started with 4.
<br />

<br />
Now you are in no way limited to 4.  8 is better, 20 is possible but its harder to control when it breaks.  You want the pet to break at about 10% health, if hes taking 30% damage per tick.. its hard to hit that without getting him at 25% sometimes.. which is a longer chant kite and less efficient or having him die and losing the XPs.
<br />

<br />
The beauty of swarming is: You get the XPs credit for the damage output of your entire swarm.  They kill the mob 90%  you kill the last 10% and get 100% of the credit.
<br />

<br />
If you do this exclusively your  defense and weapons skill will SUUUUCK in the 50s.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
